The provided information shows the structure of a dataset with 6497 rows and 13 columns. Heres a breakdown of the columns:

  • type: Character column indicating the type of wine (white or red).
  • fixed acidity: Numeric column representing the fixed acidity level of the wine.
  • volatile acidity: Numeric column representing the volatile acidity level of the wine.
  • citric acid: Numeric column representing the citric acid content in the wine.
  • residual sugar: Numeric column indicating the residual sugar content in the wine.
  • chlorides: Numeric column representing the chlorides concentration in the wine.
  • free sulfur dioxide: Numeric column indicating the concentration of free sulfur dioxide in the wine.
  • total sulfur dioxide: Numeric column indicating the total concentration of sulfur dioxide in the wine.
  • density: Numeric column representing the density of the wine.
  • pH: Numeric column representing the pH value of the wine.
  • sulphates: Numeric column indicating the sulphates concentration in the wine.
  • alcohol: Numeric column indicating the alcohol content in the wine.
  • quality: Numeric column representing the quality score of the wine.

It has been found in the heat map that the coefficient value between the attributes- density and alcohol is -0.79 and density and residual sugar is 0.71. After dropping the density attribute the coefficient value of each attribute was observed to be below 0.7 as seen in Fig. 1(b).

In the code above, we use the lm() function to fit a linear regression model with quality as the target variable and all other attributes as predictors. The summary() function is then used to obtain the coefficients and associated statistics, including the p-values. We extract the p-values using summary(model)$coefficients[, Pr(>|t|)] and store them in the p_values variable.

Interpreting the p-values:

  • (Intercept): This represents the p-value for the intercept term in the regression model. A very low p-value suggests that the intercept significantly contributes to the model.
  • typewhite: This represents the p-value for the attribute typewhite. A low p-value suggests that this attribute has a significant relationship with the outcome variable.
  • Other attributes such as fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, and pH: Each of these attributes has a corresponding p-value. A low p-value indicates that the respective attribute is statistically significant and likely has an impact on the outcome variable.

# Fit a linear regression model with all features
full_model <- lm(quality ~ ., data = wine_data)

# Define a function to calculate AIC
calculate_aic <- function(model) {
  n <- length(model$residuals)
  k <- length(model$coefficients)
  aic <- n * log(sum(model$residuals^2) / n) + 2 * k
  return(aic)
}

# Define a function to calculate BIC
calculate_bic <- function(model) {
  n <- length(model$residuals)
  k <- length(model$coefficients)
  bic <- n * log(sum(model$residuals^2) / n) + log(n) * k
  return(bic)
}

# Calculate AIC, BIC, and R-squared for the full model
full_model_aic <- calculate_aic(full_model)
full_model_bic <- calculate_bic(full_model)
full_model_r_squared <- summary(full_model)$r.squared

# Create a vector to store AIC, BIC, and R-squared values for each model
model_comparison <- data.frame(Features = "All", AIC = full_model_aic, BIC = full_model_bic, R_squared = full_model_r_squared)

# Loop through each feature and build models with subsets of features
for (i in 2:(ncol(wine_data)-1)) {
  feature_subset <- combn(names(wine_data)[-ncol(wine_data)], i)
  for (j in 1:ncol(feature_subset)) {
    subset_model <- lm(quality ~ ., data = wine_data[, c("quality", feature_subset[, j])])
    subset_model_aic <- calculate_aic(subset_model)
    subset_model_bic <- calculate_bic(subset_model)
    subset_model_r_squared <- summary(subset_model)$r.squared
    
    # Append the AIC, BIC, and R-squared values to the model comparison dataframe
    model_comparison <- rbind(model_comparison, 
                              data.frame(Features = paste(feature_subset[, j], collapse = ", "),
                                         AIC = subset_model_aic,
                                         BIC = subset_model_bic,
                                         R_squared = subset_model_r_squared))
  }
}

# Sort the model comparison dataframe by AIC in ascending order
model_comparison <- model_comparison[order(model_comparison$AIC), ]

# Print the best model with the lowest AIC
best_model <- model_comparison[1, ]
print(best_model)

Further validating our results, we rank the various attributes in our dataset by performing feature importance using Extra Trees Classifier [22,23] as shown in Fig. 3. However, the color feature is not removed from the dataset as it distinguishes the type of wine, either to be red wine or white wine.

Q2. Measure the average value of the various attributes that clearly classify the wine as a good quality wine.

To measure the average value of various attributes that clearly classify wine as good quality, you can filter the dataset based on a specific threshold for the quality variable. In this case, assuming a binary classification where a quality score of 7 or higher represents good quality wine, we can calculate the average values of attributes for those wines.

# Filter wines with quality score of 7 or higher
good_quality_wines <- wine_data[wine_data$quality >= 7, ]

# Drop the "type" column
good_quality_wines <- good_quality_wines[, -which(names(good_quality_wines) == "type")]

# Calculate the average values of attributes for good quality wines
average_attributes <- colMeans(good_quality_wines[, -ncol(good_quality_wines)])

Next, we answer the third research objective hereto get the measure of the concentration of the various attributes in red and white wine, we generate 3D visualization of a Violin Plot [27] as seen in Fig. 4. A violin plot describes the kernel density estimation [27,28] of each attribute with respect to the quality of red and white wine. A violin plot is a combination of a box plot and kernel density plot [28], which shows peaks in the data. It is used to visualize the distribution of numerical data. In fig.4, we observe that the concentration of white wine is more for quality 3 to 6 as compared to red wine. Moreover, the frequency of red wine of quality 9 is zero that is why in each violin plot where the quality is 9 there is no red wine concentration. The concentration of each attribute in white wine and red wine is determined by using the kernel density estimation. Further a comparison of both (red and white wine) concentrations is represented in the form of a violin plot for wine qualities (ranging from 3 to 9). These graphs clearly depict the concentration of selected 9 attributes with respect to wine quality, that are required to make a wine quality good. Further, wine quality which is greater than 6 is considered to be good quality wine and wine quality between 3-6 is considered as low quality or poor-quality wine.

As seen in Fig. 4. (b), concentration of pH in red wine is more as compared to white wine, between wine quality 3 to 6. Moreover, the concentration of red wine was more than that of white wine. Similarly, in the wine quality between 7 to 9(considered as good quality wine) the red wine still dominated. For Wine quality 9 red wine does not exist in the violin plot because of the absence of red wine in wine quality number 9 as shown in Fig. 4(a). As shown in Fig. 4(c), concentration of free sulfur Dioxide in low quality red wine (3 to 6) is less as compared to low quality white wine (3 to 6). For Quality between 7-9 (considered as good quality wine) the concentration in white wine dominates red wine. The concentration of residual sugar is much higher in both low-quality white wine (3 to 6) and good quality white wine (7 to 9) as compared to red wine as shown in Fig. 4(d). As seen in Fig. 4(e), the concentration of Sulphates in low quality red wine (3 to 6 wine quality) is more than the concentration low quality white wine but as we move further towards good quality wine (7 to 9 quality) the concentration in red wine increases and the white wine remains the same.

The concentration of chlorides in quality 3 to 6 (considered as low quality wine) white wine is less than red wine (quality 3-6) and as we see when the quality improves( quality 7-9) concentration of red wine is dominated in good quality red wine(7 to 8) as shown in Fig. 4 (f).The concentration of Volatile acidity in low quality red wine (quality 3 to 6) is much higher than the volatile acidity in low quality white wine(3 to 6) and as the quality improves that is in quality 7 to 9 the concentration of volatile acidity is still dominated by red wine as seen in Fig. 4(g). A seen in Fig. 4(h), the concentration of alcohol in low quality white wine (quality 3 to 6) is more than low quality red wine (quality 3 to 6) but as quality improves (quality 7 to 9) the concentration of alcohol increases in both red and white wine and alcohol concentration becomes higher in good quality red wine (quality 7-9). As seen in Fig. 4(h), the concentration of alcohol in low quality white wine (quality 3 to 6) is more than low quality red wine (quality 3 to 6) but as quality improves (quality 7 to 9) the concentration of alcohol increases in both red and white wine and alcohol concentration becomes higher in good quality red wine (quality 7-9). The concentration of citric acid as seen in Fig.4(i) for wine quality between 3 to 6 (considered as low-quality wine) is observed higher in white wine as compared to red wine but as we move further towards good quality wine (quality 7-9) we can see that concentration of red wine is dominated over white wine

Hence, we conclude that the concentration of Ph, Sulphates, Chlorides, Volatile acidity, Alcohol and Citric Acid is more in good quality red wine whereas the concentration of Free sulfur Dioxide and Residual Sugar is more in good quality white wine as compared to red wine

# Assuming you have a dataframe 'wine_data' with a column 'quality' representing wine quality values

# Define a function to map quality values to categories
map_quality <- function(quality) {
  if (quality < 5) {
    return("low")
  } else if (quality %in% c(5, 6)) {
    return("medium")
  } else if (quality >= 7) {
    return("high")
  } else {
    return(NA) # Handling other cases, if any
  }
}

# Replace 'quality' column with the mapped categories
wine_data$category <- sapply(wine_data$quality, map_quality)

# Remove the original 'quality' column
wine_data <- subset(wine_data, select = -quality)

# Print the updated dataframe
print(wine_data)
